Array operations and complexity.

Reading or updating an element by index costs constant time — one address calculation and you are there.

Searching an unsorted array costs linear time in the worst case — you may have to inspect every element before finding the target or confirming it is absent. In a sorted array, binary search brings this down to logarithmic time by halving the search space at each step.

The headline is that arrays give you the fastest possible access by index, but searching for a value you do not have the index of still means a scan, unless the data is sorted.
